1349","August 1349":"august 1349","1373":"1373","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","Abt 1378":"omkring 1378","1382":"1382","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1358":"1358","1325":"1325","1433":"1433","1378":"1378","1377":"1377","1410":"1410","1321":"1321","before 3 March 1408":"før 3. marts 1408","after 1 September 1419":"efter 1. september 1419","1408":"1408","1419":"1419","before September 1419":"før september 1419","about 1340":"omkring 1340","Halsham, Yorkshire, England":"Halsham, Jórvík, England","Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England","Swine, Yorkshire, England":"Swine, Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"about 1340–after 1 September 1419":"circa 1340–na 1 september 1419","1340–1419":"1340–1419","1350–1410":"1350–1410","–1358":"–1358","1337–1408":"1337–1408","1358–1419":"1358–1419","1378–1433":"1378–1433","1321–1377":"1321–1377","1325–1349":"1325–1349","August 1349":"augustus 1349","1373":"1373","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","Abt 1378":"circa 1378","1382":"1382","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1358":"1358","1325":"1325","1433":"1433","1378":"1378","1377":"1377","1410":"1410","1321":"1321","before 3 March 1408":"vóór 3 maart 1408","after 1 September 1419":"na 1 september 1419","1408":"1408","1419":"1419","before September 1419":"vóór september 1419","about 1340":"circa 1340","Halsham, Yorkshire, England":"Halsham, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Swine, Yorkshire, England":"Swine, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1340–after 1 September 1419":"about 1340–after 1 September 1419","1340–1419":"1340–1419","1350–1410":"1350–1410","–1358":"–1358","1337–1408":"1337–1408","1358–1419":"1358–1419","1378–1433":"1378–1433","1321–1377":"1321–1377","1325–1349":"1325–1349","August 1349":"August 1349","1373":"1373","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","Abt 1378":"about 1378","1382":"1382","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1358":"1358","1325":"1325","1433":"1433","1378":"1378","1377":"1377","1410":"1410","1321":"1321","before 3 March 1408":"before 3 March 1408","after 1 September 1419":"after 1 September 1419","1408":"1408","1419":"1419","before September 1419":"before September 1419","about 1340":"about 1340","Halsham, Yorkshire, England":"Halsham, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Swine, Yorkshire, England":"Swine, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hilton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire):","habitational name from any of various places called Hilton (e.g. in Cambridgeshire, Derbyshire, Staffordshire, North Yorkshire, and Westmorland), most of which derive from Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some come from Old English <i>helde</i> ‘slope’ + <i>tūn</i>.","occasionally, as in the case of Ralph <i>filius Hilton</i> (Yorkshire 1219), perhaps from the personal name <i>Hilton</i>, itself a possible form of Norman <i>Hildun</i>, composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’ + <i>hūn</i> ‘bear cub’. Compare   Hilt  . This English surname is present in Ireland (mainly taken to Ulster in the early 17th century, though recorded earlier in Dublin)."],"variants":[{"name":"Hylton","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Hilton  ."]},{"name":"Hulton","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Hulton (Lancashire) or Hulton (Staffordshire), both from Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Hilton  ."]},{"name":"Hilt","meanings":["German: from a short form of   Hildebrand   or some other compound ancient Germanic name formed with <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’ as the first element. See   Hild  .","English (London): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hilte</i>, ultimately from ancient Germanic <i>Helto</i>, probably from <i>halith-</i> ‘hero’."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Hilton was born about 1340, in Swine, Yorkshire, England, her father, Robert Hilton, was 20 and her mother, Matilda Campania, was 16. She married Sir John Constable II in 1373. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died after 1 September 1419, in Halsham, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"about 1340–after 1 September 1419":"umbes 1340–pärast 1. septembrit 1419","1340–1419":"1340–1419","1350–1410":"1350–1410","–1358":"–1358","1337–1408":"1337–1408","1358–1419":"1358–1419","1378–1433":"1378–1433","1321–1377":"1321–1377","